1 Computer Programs and Software

2 WIPO: Model Provisions (1978)

Section 1, WIPO Model Provisions on the Protection of Computer Programs (1978)

(i) "computer program" means a set of instructions capable, when incorporated in a machine-readable medium, of causing a machine having information-processing capabilities to indicate, perform or achieve a particular function, task or result;

(ii) "program description" means a complete procedural presentation in verbal, schematic or other form, in sufficient detail to determine a set of instructions constituting a corresponding computer program;

(iii) "supporting material" means any material, other than a computer program or a program description, created for aiding the understanding or application of a computer program, for example problem descriptions and user instructions;

(iv) "computer software" means any or several of the items referred to in (i) to (iii);

(v) "proprietor" means the person, including a
legal entity, to whom the rights under this Law belong
according to Section 2(1). or his successor in title
according to Section 2(2).

4 Source code in Fortran

 1: program mandelbrot
 2:  
 3:   implicit none
 4:   integer  , parameter :: rk       = selected_real_kind (9, 99)
 5:   integer  , parameter :: i_max    =  800
 6:   integer  , parameter :: j_max    =  600
 7:   integer  , parameter :: n_max    =  100
 8:   real (rk), parameter :: x_centre = -0.5_rk
 9:   real (rk), parameter :: y_centre =  0.0_rk
10:   real (rk), parameter :: width    =  4.0_rk
11:   real (rk), parameter :: height   =  3.0_rk
12:   real (rk), parameter :: dx_di    =   width / i_max
13:   real (rk), parameter :: dy_dj    = -height / j_max
14:   real (rk), parameter :: x_offset = x_centre - 0.5_rk * (i_max + 1) * dx_di
15:   real (rk), parameter :: y_offset = y_centre - 0.5_rk * (j_max + 1) * dy_dj
16:   integer, dimension (i_max, j_max) :: image
17:   integer   :: i
18:   integer   :: j
19:   integer   :: n
20:   real (rk) :: x
21:   real (rk) :: y
22:   real (rk) :: x_0
23:   real (rk) :: y_0
24:   real (rk) :: x_sqr
25:   real (rk) :: y_sqr
26:  
27:   do j = 1, j_max
28:     y_0 = y_offset + dy_dj * j
29:     do i = 1, i_max
30:       x_0 = x_offset + dx_di * i
31:       x = 0.0_rk
32:       y = 0.0_rk
33:       n = 0
34:       do
35:         x_sqr = x ** 2
36:         y_sqr = y ** 2
37:         if (x_sqr + y_sqr > 4.0_rk) then
38:           image (i, j) = 255
39:           exit
40:         end if
41:         if (n == n_max) then
42:           image (i, j) = 0
43:           exit
44:         end if
45:         y = y_0 + 2.0_rk * x * y
46:         x = x_0 + x_sqr - y_sqr
47:         n = n + 1
48:       end do
49:     end do
50:   end do
51:   open  (10, file = 'out.png')
52:   write (10, '(a/ i0, 1x, i0/ i0)') 'P2', i_max, j_max, 255
53:   write (10, '(i0)') image
54:   close (10)
55:  
56: end program mandelbrot

source: https://rosettacode.org/wiki/Mandelbrot_set GNU Free Documentation License 1.2 (Rosetta Code was created in January 2007 by Mike Mol)

5 Compile source code into object code

  • about the compiler: https://gcc.gnu.org/wiki/GFortran
  • run the follow code from a CLI
    gfortran mandelbrot-source-code.f90 -o mandelbrot-object-code

10 Source code is communicative

Source code is useful (at least potentially) to every user of a program. But most users are not allowed to have copies of the source code. Usually the source code for a proprietary program is kept secret by the owner, lest anybody else learn something from it. Users receive only the files of incomprehensible numbers that the computer will execute. This means that only the program's owner can change the program. Richard Stallman, Why Software Should Be Free, 1991, at
http://www.gnu.org/philosophy/shouldbefree.html
